}}
At [[Metacritic]], they assign a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score to ratings and reviews from mainstream music critics, and based upon eleven of those for the 35th Anniversary Reissue Box Set, the album Metascore is a 99 out of 100.<ref name=METACRITIC>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/rumours-35th-anniversary-deluxe-edition/fleetwood-mac/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Rumours Rumours &#91;35th Anniversary Deluxe Edition&#93;|author=Metacritic|date=29 January 2013|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> At ''[[American Songwriter]]'', Steven Rosen called this "their finest" release, which "addresses with heart and sharp insight the romantic disengagements and re-entanglements of the members in the free-spirited, free-love 1970s."<ref name=AMERICANSONGWRITER/> Jon Hadusek of [[Consequence of Sound]] proclaimed that the album still "endures" because he found "what makes ''Rumours'' so remarkable and relevant is that it remains fragile and passionate 35 years later."<ref name=CONSEQUENCEOFSOUND/> Andy Gill of ''[[The Independent]]'' observed an "enduring quality" in the album and asserted that it "represents, along with ''[[Their Greatest Hits (1971<U+2013>1975)|The Eagles Greatest Hits]]'', the high-water mark of America's Seventies rock-culture expansion, the quintessence of a counter-cultural mindset lured into coke-fuelled hedonism."<ref name=THEINDEPENDENT/> At ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', James McNair found that "''Rumours'' reminds us why we should continue to indulge them."<ref name=MOJO/> Ryan Reed of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' told that the release is a "unique blend of heavy and playful, mystical and muscular", and this is the reason this album "deserves the lavish, borderline-unnecessary reissue treatment, it's this pop behemoth."<ref name=PASTE/> 

[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'s Jessica Hopper said that it is "one of classic rock's foundational" releases, which it is a "flawless record pulled from the wreckage of real lives", and this makes "it [hold] up better than any other commercial smash of that ilk".<ref name=PITCHFORK/> In addition, Hopper noted that "''Rumours'' was not exactly a game changer, it was merely perfect."<ref name=PITCHFORK/> At ''Rolling Stone'', Jody Rosen evoked how past listeners who purchased the album "know its glories <U+2013> the uncanny fusion of pop hooks, 1950s rock exuberance and heavenly harmonies", and found that "the real revelations are recordings that part the curtains on the making of ''Rumours'', like Christine McVie's solo-piano-demo rendition of 'Songbird.'"<ref name=ROLLINGSTONE/> Piers Martin of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' noted that "for all the baubles and padding presented with this definitive edition, the disc you'll turn to again and again is the one you've been playing all your life", which is an album with a "lurid backstory of emotional turmoil and narcotic excess, endlessly recounted in prurient detail, is never less than fascinating."<ref name=UNCUT/> At ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]'', Frank Valish found that the reissue "does the original album, and its story, justice."<ref name=UNDERTHERADAR/> However, [[PopMatters]]' John Bergstorm told that "every song is an open-and-shut case, a tightly-sealed, end-of-story work of pop-rock perfection", this is the reason he believed "items like discs of live material and outtakes are superfluous at best."<ref name=POPMATTERS/>

==Legacy==
Mick Fleetwood has called ''Rumours'' "the most important album we ever made", because its success allowed the group to continue recording for years to come.<ref>''Classic Albums'', c. 56:05<U+2013>56:25</ref> [[Pop culture]] journalist [[Chuck Klosterman]] links the record's sales figures to its "really likable songs", but suggests that "no justification for greatness" is intrinsically provided by them.<ref name=pop>{{cite book |author=Klosterman, Chuck|title=This Is Pop: In Search of the Elusive at Experience Music Project|trans_title=The Carly Simon Principle: Sincerity and Pop Greatness|year=2004|editor=Weisbard, Eric|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|isbn=0-674-01321-2 |pages=261<U+2013>262}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' collated worldwide data in 1997 from a range of renowned critics, artists, and radio DJs, who placed the record at number&nbsp;78 in the list of the 100 Best Albums Ever.<ref>{{Cite news |title=100 Best Albums Ever|work=The Guardian |location=UK|at=''Features'' insert|date=19 September 1997}}</ref> In 1998, ''Legacy: A Tribute to Fleetwood Mac's Rumours'' was produced by Fleetwood and released. The record contained each song of the original ''Rumours'' [[cover (music)|covered]] by a different act influenced by it. Among the musicians involved were [[alternative rock]] bands [[Tonic (band)|Tonic]], [[Matchbox 20]], and [[Goo Goo Dolls]], Celtic rock groups [[The Corrs]] and [[The Cranberries]], and singer-songwriters [[Elton John]], [[Duncan Sheik]], and [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5918517/rumours_tribute_available_now|title="Rumours" Tribute Available Now|work=Rolling Stone|date=28 March 1998|accessdate=28 December 2009}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref> Other diverse acts influenced by ''Rumours'' include [[baroque pop]] artist [[Tori Amos]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=America at Her Gait|author=Brown, Mark|work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|page=7E|date=4 December 2002}}</ref> [[hard rock]] group [[Saliva (band)|Saliva]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=To Drool For|author=Keyes, Bob|work=[[Portland Press Herald]]|page=3D|date=30 January 2003}}</ref> and [[indie rock]] band [[Death Cab for Cutie]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Death Cab Hails Wide Range of Musical Fare As Influences|author=Brown, Mark|work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|page=9E|date=7 October 2005}}</ref>

{{quote box|quote="There was a time when Fleetwood Mac's ''Rumours'' was just seen as an album that sold incredibly well; over the past five years, though, it's become more acceptable to classify ''Rumours'' as great in and of itself."<ref name=pop/>|source=<U+2014>[[Chuck Klosterman]] in 2004, on recognition for the record|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:10px;}}

In 1998, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' placed ''Rumours'' at number three<U+2014>behind [[The Clash]]'s ''[[London Calling]]'' and [[Pink Floyd]]'s ''[[The Dark Side of the Moon]]''<U+2014>in its list of 50&nbsp;Best Albums of the&nbsp;70s.<ref>{{Cite news |title=50 Best Albums of the 70s|author=''Q'' staff|work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|at=pull-out section|date=April 1998}}</ref> In 1999, [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']] featured it as one of 100&nbsp;Essential Albums of the 20th&nbsp;Century.<ref>{{Cite news |title=100 Essential Albums of the 20th Century|author=''Vibe'' staff|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|page=162|date=December 1999}}</ref> In 2003, [[VH1]] ranked the record at number&nbsp;16 during its 100&nbsp;Greatest Albums countdown,<ref name=pop/> while ''Slant'' included it as one of 50&nbsp;Essential Pop Albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/features/vitalpop.asp|author=Slant staff|title=Vitalpop!|work=[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]|year=2003|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref> The same year, ''[[USA Today]]'' placed ''Rumours'' at number&nbsp;23 in its Top 40&nbsp;Albums list,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2003-12-04-album-list_x.htm|author=Gundersen, Edna|title=Top 40 albums<U+2014>the USA Today way|work=USA Today|date=5 December 2003|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref> while ''Rolling Stone'' ranked it at number&nbsp;25 in its special issue of "[[The 500&nbsp;Greatest Albums of All Time]]", the highest Fleetwood Mac record.<ref name="RSLIST">{{Cite news |title=The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|author=''Rolling Stone'' staff|work=Rolling Stone|page=104|date=12 November 2003}}</ref> In 2006, ''Time'' named it in its All-TIME 100&nbsp;Albums shortlist,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/0,27693,Rumours,00.html|author=Tyrangiel, Josh|title=The All-TIME 100 Albums|work=Time|date=13 November 2006|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref> while ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' featured it in its unnumbered list&nbsp;of&nbsp;70 from the 1970s: Decade<U+2019>s Greatest Albums.<ref>{{Cite news |title=70 from the 1970s: Decade's Greatest Albums|author=''Mojo'' staff|work=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|at=pull-out section|date=June 2006}}</ref> The record is included in both ''The Guardian''{{'}}s "1000&nbsp;Albums to Hear Before You Die" and the book ''[[1001&nbsp;Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref name=g1000>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2007/nov/19/1000tohearbeforeyoudie3|title=Artists beginning with F (1000 Albums to Hear Before You Die)|work=The Guardian |location=UK|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor=Dimery, Richard|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die|year=2008 |publisher=[[Orion Publishing Group|Cassell Illustrated]]|isbn=1-84403-624-3}}</ref> In the 2013 reissue of the album, [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Jessica Hopper gave the album a rare 10 out of 10, earning it best new reissue.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hopper |first=Jessica |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17499-rumours/ |title=Fleetwood Mac: Rumours &#124; Album Reviews |publisher=Pitchfork |date=8 February 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref>

In 2011, the television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', had a "[[Rumours (Glee)|Rumours]]" episode that used six songs from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/on-glee-the-rumours-have-it-20110504|title=Rumour Has It: 'Glee' Takes on Fleetwood Mac|work=Rolling Stone|date=4 May 2011|author=Futterman, Erica|accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Semigran|first=Aly|title=Fleetwood Mac Teach 'Glee' Kids a Lesson on Rumours:New Directions took on six songs from the classic album as their own internal strife mirrored the band's|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1663211/glee-fleetwood-mac-rumours.jhtml|publisher=MTV|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref> The episode renewed interest in the album, and ''Rumours'' re-entered the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart at #11.  This was the highest chart entry by a previously issued album since [[the Rolling Stones]]' ''[[Exile on Main St.]]'' re-entered the chart at number 2 on 5 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Beastie Boys Score No. 2 Debut on Billboard 200, Adele Holds at No. 1|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/471634/beastie-boys-score-no-2-debut-on-billboard-200-adele-holds-at-no-1|work=Billboard|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref>

